function shortestPath(grid, k) {
    const m = grid.length;
    const n = grid[0].length;
    const queue = [[0, 0, 0, k]];
    const visited = new Array(m).fill(null).map(() => new Array(n).fill(null).map(() => new Array(k + 1).fill(false)));

    while (queue.length) {
        const [x, y, step, remainingK] = queue.shift();

        if (x === m - 1 && y === n - 1) return step;
        if (visited[x][y][remainingK]) continue;
        visited[x][y][remainingK] = true;

        const directions = [[-1, 0], [1, 0], [0, -1], [0, 1]];

        for (const [dx, dy] of directions) {
            const nx = x + dx;
            const ny = y + dy;

            if (nx >= 0 && nx < m && ny >= 0 && ny < n) {
                if (grid[nx][ny] === 1 && remainingK > 0) {
                    queue.push([nx, ny, step + 1, remainingK - 1]);
                } else if (grid[nx][ny] === 0) {
                    queue.push([nx, ny, step + 1, remainingK]);
                }
            }
        }
    }

    return -1;
}
```

    We use Breadth-First Search (BFS) algorithm to explore the grid. We maintain a queue to store the current status of the cell (x, y, step) as well as the remaining obstacles that we can eliminate (remaining_k). We initialize the queue with (0, 0, 0, k).

We then iterate through the queue until it's empty, in each iteration we pop the front element and check if we reach the bottom-right corner (m-1, n-1). If yes, we return the number of steps. If not, we mark the cell as visited and try to explore the neighbors in all four directions (up, down, left, right). If the neighbor cell has an obstacle and we have remaining_k > 0, we can eliminate the obstacle and add the neighbor cell into the queue with its new status. If the neighbor cell has no obstacle, we can simply add it to the queue.

After the iteration through the queue, if we haven't found a valid path to (m-1, n-1), we return -1.

The time complexity of this algorithm is O(m * n * k) because we potentially need to traverse all m * n cells, multiplied by k because we are keeping track of k states at each cell.

